5 If any one shall seem to be the author of division or dissension among those who live together, or with their Head; he shall be separated with all diligence from that congregation, as a plagae which will infect the whole, if an immediate remedy be not ap- phed.

6 On the part of the General, these are the qualities which con· duce to this mental union, and with which, as is set forth in the Ninth Part, be ought to be endowed: and provided with these, he shall do his duty to every member of the Society,the duty, namely, of Head, namely‚ from whom the influence necessary to the office assigned to him shall descend: and thus from the General, as from the Head, all the power of the Provincials shall issue, and through them to local Superiora, and through them it shall resch individual members: so also, from the same Head (or at least from bis deputation of authority, and with his approval) shall the missione proceed. Let thus much suffice on the communi- cation of the powers of the Society. For the more inferiora depend upon their Superiora, the better the love of Obedience and Union will be preserved between them.

7 And to the end that position may be more conducive to the in· tercourse of the head with its members; it will be most proper that the General should chiefly reside at Rome, where be can enjoy the readiest intercourse with all other places of the Society.
